			"contents": "Searching 259 files for \"canzoom\" (regex)\n\n~/Sites/mrbmc/src/_js/portfolio.js:\n  102  window.addEventListener('load', function(e) {\n  103      console.log('project.window.load',e);\n  104:     var zoomies = document.querySelectorAll('.canzoom');\n  105      Object.entries(zoomies).forEach(([key, zoomy]) => {\n  106          console.log(`${key}: ${zoomy}`)\n\n~/Sites/mrbmc/src/_scss/pages/project.scss:\n   13          p {\n   14              &>img,&>svg,&>video {\n   15:                 &.canzoom {\n   16                      transition: all lib.$speed lib.$easing;\n   17                      &:hover {\n\n~/Sites/mrbmc/src/projects/blogtalkradio.md:\n  134  <p>The art direction was inspired by high-end Audio and video authoring applications. We wanted to convey a serious, professional-grade application for our hosts to work with.</p>\n  135  \n  136: + !['Live'](/images/portfolio/btr/btr-studio-live.png) {.col-4 .row-1 .canzoom .contain}\n  137  + !['Pre-Show'](/images/portfolio/btr/btr-studio-pre-show.png) {.col-4 .row-1}\n  138  + !['Ad Break'](/images/portfolio/btr/btr-studio-ad-break.png) {.col-4 .row-1}\n\n~/Sites/mrbmc/src/projects/disney-groupwatch.md:\n   60  The Visiontype is a powerful tool for gaining stakeholder buy-in, feeding user research studies, and communicating with other teams.\n   61  \n   62: ![WeWatch Visiontype](/images/portfolio/disney-groupwatch/groupwatch-visiontype-mocks.png){.canzoom}\n   63  \n   64  ### Proof of concept\n   ..\n   94  \n   95  Principles are a powerful way to align teams in big programs and guide decisions about tradeoffs in the design. Principles must address the specific user goals and business constraints of a project. Generic principles about \"ease of use\" and \"delightful\" do not aid critical thinking in a specific context.\n   96: ![](/images/portfolio/disney-groupwatch/groupwatch-tenets.png){.canzoom} \n   97  \n   98  <!--\n   ..\n  135  \n  136  Two designers and a researcher partnered to refine the invite UI. Using Rapid Iterative Test Evaluation tested prototypes with users to learn more about their mental models and identify any usabilty issues. This was the first prototype flow:\n  137: ![Invite flow version 1](/images/portfolio/disney-groupwatch/groupwatch-invite-v1.png){.canzoom}\n  138  \n  139  Testing convinced the team to make big changes: \n  ...\n  141  - Leverage the native social features in phones. \n  142  - Lean into the \"theater lobby\" metaphor of the social gathering.\n  143: ![Invite flow version 2](/images/portfolio/disney-groupwatch/groupwatch-invite-v2.png){.canzoom}\n  144  \n  145  ### Visual Design\n  ...\n  149  1. Visual design started with a broad spectrum of divergent ideas. We began to read-in more designers to the project at this point.\n  150  \n  151: ![24 versions of the waiting room](/images/portfolio/disney-groupwatch/groupwatch-visual-v1.jpg){.canzoom}\n  152  \n  153  \n  154  2. We focused on layouts that had the right balance of social and content priority.\n  155  \n  156: ![Waiting room layouts that balance social and content](/images/portfolio/disney-groupwatch/groupwatch-visual-v2.jpg){.canzoom}\n  157  \n  158  3. Engineering leads had been informed of the program but now was the point we dug deep with Client Engineers to identify expensive UI that couldn't be rendered or needed custom components.\n  159  \n  160: ![Waiting room layouts that are feasible](/images/portfolio/disney-groupwatch/groupwatch-visual-v3.jpg){.canzoom}\n  161  \n  162  4. Finally, we aligned to the existing visual style as much as possible so the feature would feel native and intentional.\n  163  \n  164: ![Waiting room designs that fit our visual language](/images/portfolio/disney-groupwatch/groupwatch-visual-v4.jpg){.canzoom}\n  165  \n  166  \n\n~/Sites/mrbmc/src/projects/disney-growth-long.md:\n   78  The Growth Design team began work long before Disney+ launched; before Disney acquired BAMTech to build its streaming services; even before BAMTech existed. Many of the people on the teams involved had already launched & operated dozens of direct-to-consumer services as part of *MLB Advanced Media*.\n   79  \n   80: ![streaming services we launched](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/mlbam-clients-grayscale.png){.canzoom}\n   81  \n   82  Disney acquired BAMTech for its ability to build *content businesses*. In addition to the technology for streaming high-quality video over the internet, BAMTech had the commerce platform turnstile UX to sell content directly to consumers at scale. That experience gave us a basecamp from which to begin our expedition up Disney+. We already had the infrastructure for many core Growth features:\n   ..\n  265  Existing accounts would be confirmed with an email confirmation containing a One Time Passcode. Once Confirmed, we could use the existing account to grant entitlements for streaming. Net new emails would create a new account by setting a password.\n  266  \n  267: ![Signup Web](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/Disney_SVOD_Product_Overview_Onboarding.032.jpeg){.canzoom}\n  268  Signup for Web{.caption}\n  269  \n  270: ![Signup Apple Mobile](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/Disney_SVOD_Product_Overview_Onboarding.101.jpeg){.canzoom}\n  271  Signup for Apple Mobile{.caption}\n  272  \n  ...\n  274  \n  275  We debated whether the success screen was truly necessary. From a functional stand-point it wasn't, and our tenet \"First Stream First\" suggested that we should remove it. On the other-hand there was a usability argument that any commerce transaction needs to communicate its status to the user.\n  276: ![success screen](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/signup-web-success-v1.jpeg){.canzoom}\n  277  \n  278  Ultimately the debate was settled by... you guessed it ... *licensing agreements!*\n  ...\n  282  The least awful place for us to advertise another service was at the end of the purchase funnel. We also removed the prompt to setup profiles in service of that \"First Stream...\" tenet to prevent any distractions. \n  283  \n  284: ![Starz Wars](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/StarzSept06final.006.jpeg){.canzoom}\n  285  \n  286  ### TV & Connected Devices {#tv-signup}\n  ...\n  351  In order to get this solution to market more efficiently the first shipped version would only have the license plate code – no QR code – and we had to remove the progress screens.\n  352  \n  353: ![](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/tv-signup-live.jpg){.canzoom}\n  354  \n  355  #### Outcomes\n  ...\n  373  We designed a scalable framework that could adapt to different billing capabilities or local regulations. We also designed materials for our Partnership team to help onboard resellers and developers.\n  374  \n  375: ![B2B2C OneSheet](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/Disney+_B2B2C_OneSheet.jpg){.canzoom}\n  376  \n  377  \n  ...\n  408  Latin America required additional fields for Tax collection in Argentina and Chile\n  409  \n  410: ![payment forms](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/disney+-signup-AR-step_4.png){.canzoom}\n  411  \n  412  #### Outcomes\n\n~/Sites/mrbmc/src/projects/disney-growth.md:\n  243  Latin America required additional fields for Tax collection in Argentina and Chile\n  244  \n  245: ![payment forms](/images/portfolio/disney-growth/disney+-signup-AR-step_4.png){.canzoom}\n  246  \n  247  #### Outcomes\n\n20 matches across 6 files\n",
